'''Karatoyama Kofun''' (唐櫃山古墳) is a {{ill|scallop-shaped kofun|ja|帆立貝形古墳|1=scallop-shaped kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/scallop-shaped kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/scallop-shaped kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} located in Kokufu, [[Fujidera City]], [[:en:Osaka Prefecture|Osaka Prefecture]]. It is one of the kofun typeing the [[:en:Furuichi Kofun Cluster|Furuichi Kofun Group]], a Historic Site1 [[National Historic Site of Japan]]. The stone coffin from this site is Historic Site1 as a Fujidera City tangible cultural property.

The kofun was situated outside the moat of [[:en:Ichinoyama Kofun|Ichinoyama Kofun]]. In 1955, road construction destroyed most of the mound, leaving only the northern portion as part of a private garden. Emergency excavations yielded a {{ill|stone coffin|ja|石棺|1=Sekkan|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/stone coffin|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekkan|qq=}} and burial goods.

== Overview ==
The mound measures 53 meters in length, with a rear circular section 38 meters in diameter and 21 meters wide at the front section. The mound was largely destroyed during the construction of the {{ill|Osaka Prefecture Route 12 and Nara Prefecture Route 12|ja|大阪府道・奈良県道12号堺大和高田線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Osaka Prefecture Route 12 and Nara Prefecture Route 12|qq=|1=Osaka Prefectural Road and Nara Prefectural Road Route 12|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11441406}}. Prior to its destruction, archaeologist Kohei Kitano conducted an excavation. A {{ill|pit-style stone chamber|ja|竪穴式石槨|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/pit-style stone chamber|13=User:Immanuelle/Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 竪穴式石室}} was identified, aligned parallel to the mound's main axis in the rear circular section, containing a {{ill|house-shaped stone coffin|ja|家形石棺|1=House-shaped Sarcophagus|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/house-shaped stone coffin|13=User:Immanuelle/House-shaped Sarcophagus|qq=}}. The coffin was remarkably similar to one of the coffins from {{ill|Nagamochiyama Kofun|ja|長持山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagamochiyama Kofun|qq=}} and made from the same Aso welded tuff.<ref>Amano "Basic Research" (2008), p. 72</ref>.

== burial goods and Dating ==
Although the burial chamber had been looted, numerous small glass beads and round beads were recovered from inside the coffin. burial goods found outside the coffin included a gilt bronze tri-wheel bead, deer antler sword fittings, swords, iron arrowheads, two sets of triangular iron plate armor, and horse gear. Excavations conducted by the Osaka Prefecture Board of Education in 1981 and 2000, related to road widening projects, uncovered parts of the rear section and moat. burial goods recovered included {{ill|cylindrical haniwa|ja|円筒埴輪|1=Cylindrical Haniwa|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/cylindrical haniwa|13=User:Immanuelle/Cylindrical Haniwa|qq=}}, morning-glory-shaped haniwa, house-shaped haniwa, and chicken-shaped haniwa, dating the kofun to the mid-5th century, contemporary with [[:en:Ichinoyama Kofun|Ichinoyama Kofun]].<ref>Ichinose "Basic Research" (2008), p. 196</ref>.

A 2009 excavation also uncovered fragments of umbrella-shaped haniwa, shield-shaped haniwa, and cylindrical haniwa. These haniwa were made from both Haji and Sue-type clays, with Sue-type haniwa being more prevalent. The cylindrical haniwa shared characteristics with those from the outer embankment of Ichinoyama Kofun, suggesting they came from the same kiln.<ref>Nishikawa "Karatoyama Kofun" (2011), pp. 14-34</ref>. Fukiishi (covering stones) recovered from the moat were found to consist of approximately 70% stones from the nearby Ishikawa River, with the remainder sourced from the Yamato River and Haragawa River.

== Historic Site ==
=== National Historic Site ===
* Karatoyama Kofun (part of the "Furuichi Kofun Group") - A11ed to the existing Historic Site of the "Furuichi Kofun Group" on March 10, 2015.<ref>March 10, 2015: MEXT Notification No. 43</ref>.

=== Fujidera City-Designated Historic Site ===
* Tangible designation1
** Stone coffin from Karatoyama Kofun (archaeological material) - Designated on March 24, 2022.

